-- в”Ђв”Ђ AstroNvim в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$AstroNvim is a free, open-source Neovim configuration framework that turns the plain text editor into a full-featured, IDE-like coding environment out of the box.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$open-source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE(NULL, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$AstroNvim Review 2026: Features, Setup and Plugins$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$AstroNvim is a free, open-source Neovim config framework with built-in LSP, autocompletion and file explorer. See features, setup steps and community plugins for 2026.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$AstroNvim is a free and open-source configuration framework for Neovim, the terminal-based text editor descended from Vim. Rather than being a standalone application, AstroNvim is a curated, pre-built collection of Neovim plugins and settings, distributed as a Lua-based configuration repository on GitHub, that transforms a bare Neovim install into a polished, IDE-like development environment with almost no manual setup. It is maintained by the AstroNvim open-source organization and a volunteer community rather than a commercial company, and it has no pricing, subscriptions, or paid tiers since it is entirely free software released publicly on GitHub. The project has become one of the most popular Neovim distributions, alongside alternatives like LazyVim and LunarVim, and has attracted tens of thousands of GitHub stars along with an active Discord server and community-run plugin marketplace called AstroCommunity, which offers more than 40 ready-to-install language packs. Core features include automatic language server, linter, and formatter installation through the bundled Mason package manager, a Neo-tree file explorer, Treesitter-based syntax highlighting, Gitsigns git integration, a Heirline-powered statusline and bufferline, integrated terminal via Toggleterm, fuzzy finding, and native Language Server Protocol and Debug Adapter Protocol support. AstroNvim's architecture is modular: its configuration is built as a set of individual plugin specs that behave like ordinary Neovim plugins, so users can add, remove, or override any piece without learning a bespoke configuration language. Extensive lazy-loading keeps startup times fast even with a large plugin set. The target audience is developers, students, and terminal power users who want a fast, keyboard-driven coding environment without hand-assembling a Neovim config from scratch, but who still want full control to customize it. Compared to VS Code or JetBrains IDEs, AstroNvim is far lighter-weight, runs entirely in the terminal, and requires more comfort with keyboard-centric workflows, but it starts near-instantly and consumes a fraction of the memory. Compared to other Neovim distributions like LazyVim, AstroNvim is generally considered slightly more configuration-heavy and community-plugin-driven, while LunarVim and NvChad take somewhat different structural approaches. Because it is entirely open source under a permissive license and requires no account, signup, or payment, AstroNvim carries no vendor lock-in risk: users can always fork the configuration or eject to a plain Neovim setup.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '974f7a00-1d67-447e-9058-bf05fe6357ad';

