-- в”Ђв”Ђ Athenahealth в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Athenahealth is a healthcare technology company providing cloud-based electronic health records, practice management, and medical billing software for medical practices and health systems.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$custom$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE(NULL, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(1997, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE($q$approx 8,800 employees$q$, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE($q$Boston, Massachusetts, USA$q$, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Athenahealth Review 2026: EHR, Billing and Pricing$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Athenahealth offers cloud-based EHR, practice management, and medical billing software for healthcare providers. See athenaOne features, history, and pricing for 2026.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Athenahealth is a healthcare technology company that provides cloud-based electronic health records (EHR), practice management, medical billing, and patient engagement software to medical practices and health systems across the United States. The company was founded in 1997 by Jonathan Bush and Todd Park, originally starting as a women's health and birthing practice in San Diego before pivoting into healthcare software; it later relocated its headquarters to the Boston, Massachusetts area and went public in 2007. Athenahealth's flagship offering today is athenaOne, an integrated cloud-based suite that bundles athenaClinicals, its electronic health records and clinical documentation module, athenaCollector, its revenue cycle management and medical billing service, and athenaCommunicator, its patient engagement and care coordination tools, alongside the Epocrates mobile clinical reference app it acquired in 2013. The company has grown substantially through acquisitions, including RazorInsights and webOMR technology in 2015, and underwent major ownership changes in the years since: activist investor Elliott Management pushed for a sale in 2018, and Veritas Capital and Evergreen Coast Capital acquired athenahealth for approximately 5.7 billion dollars in a deal completed in February 2019, merging it with Virence Health, the former GE Healthcare IT business. In February 2022, Bain Capital and Hellman and Friedman acquired athenahealth for roughly 17 billion dollars, one of the largest private equity transactions in healthcare IT history, and the company has remained privately held since. As of recent company disclosures, athenahealth employs around 8,800 people and its network connects more than 170,000 providers, processing over 315 million medical claims annually and touching more than a fifth of the US population through its client base. Athenahealth targets ambulatory healthcare practices of varying sizes, from small independent practices to larger multi-specialty groups and health systems, and it does not publish list pricing; prospective customers get custom quotes based on practice size, specialty, and which modules (EHR, billing, patient engagement) they adopt, often combined with a percentage-of-collections billing model for its revenue cycle services rather than a flat per-user subscription fee. Its main competitors in the ambulatory EHR and practice management space include Epic, Cerner (Oracle Health), eClinicalWorks, NextGen Healthcare, and Kareo (Tebra), with athenahealth generally positioned as a cloud-native, services-heavy alternative that bundles billing operations support alongside its software rather than selling software alone.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = 'af325440-f24d-415b-86fc-e363e0fc59ca';

