-- в”Ђв”Ђ Attendize в”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђв”Ђ
UPDATE tools SET
  short_description = COALESCE($q$Attendize is a free, open-source, self-hosted ticket selling and event management platform built on Laravel, offering an alternative to paid platforms like Eventbrite.$q$, short_description),
  pricing_model = COALESCE($q$open-source$q$, pricing_model),
  starting_price = COALESCE(NULL, starting_price),
  founded_year = COALESCE(NULL, founded_year),
  company_size = COALESCE(NULL, company_size),
  headquarters = COALESCE(NULL, headquarters),
  languages = ARRAY[$q$English$q$]::text[],
  seo_title = COALESCE($q$Attendize Review 2026: Open-Source Ticketing Platform$q$, seo_title),
  seo_meta_description = COALESCE($q$Attendize is a free, self-hosted, open-source event ticketing platform built on Laravel. See its features, setup requirements, and current maintenance status.$q$, seo_meta_description),
  llm_readable_summary = COALESCE($q$Attendize is an open-source event ticketing and management platform built on the Laravel PHP framework, distributed as free code on GitHub rather than as a hosted commercial product. It positions itself as a self-hosted alternative to paid ticketing platforms such as Eventbrite, letting event organizers sell tickets and manage attendees on their own servers without paying per-ticket service fees to a third party. Core features include mobile-friendly, customizable event pages, attendee management with refund and messaging tools, customizable tickets with QR codes and organizer branding, data export of attendee lists to formats like CSV and XLS, real-time event statistics, support for unlimited organizers and events on a single install, multiple currency support, affiliate tracking to measure referral sales, widget support for embedding ticket-selling widgets into external websites or WordPress blogs, and integration with payment gateways such as Stripe and PayPal to process transactions directly. The platform is released under the Attribution Assurance License and requires a standard LAMP-style stack to self-host, including PHP 7.1.3 or higher, MySQL 5.7 or higher, and several common PHP extensions, with Docker-based deployment options available to simplify setup. Because it is purely self-hosted open-source software, Attendize has no company behind it in the traditional sense, no disclosed founding year, headquarters, or employee count, and no official hosted SaaS version at attendize.com; some third-party providers offer managed hosting for Attendize as a paid convenience service, and a white-label commercial licensing option has historically been referenced in its documentation. Development activity has slowed significantly: the most recent tagged release, version 2.8.0, dates to early 2023, and the GitHub repository has a large backlog of open issues and pull requests, which means the project should be considered lightly maintained rather than actively developed, and self-hosters should expect to handle security patching themselves. Attendize is best suited to technically capable organizers, developers, or small event companies who want full control and no per-ticket fees and are comfortable managing their own server, database, and updates, as opposed to those who want a fully managed, actively supported SaaS ticketing product. Its natural comparison points are other self-hosted or open-source event platforms, and on the commercial SaaS side, Eventbrite, Tito, and Hi.Events.$q$, llm_readable_summary),
  status = 'published',
  noindex = false,
  sitemap_eligible = true,
  published_at = COALESCE(published_at, now()),
  updated_at = now()
WHERE id = '309b9728-2f66-4911-9e11-c40f64054a67';

